 Explain the difference between git pull, git fetch, and git clone. When would you use each?

​1. git clone
​ It creates a brand-new, exact copy of a remote repository on your local machine. It downloads all the files, branches, and the entire commit history from scratch.
​ Use this at the very beginning of a project when you want to download an existing repository from GitHub to your computer for the first time.
​

2. git fetch
​ It downloads any new updates (like commits or new branches) from the remote repository to your local system's hidden .git folder, but it does not change any of the actual files you are currently working on. It just safely updates your system's awareness of what has changed online.
​ Use this when you want to review what your teammates have been working on before you decide to merge their changes into your own local files.
​

3. git pull
​ It does two commands at once: it fetches the updates from the remote repository and immediately merges them into your current working files. (git pull = git fetch + git merge).
​ Use this when you want your local files to be completely up-to-date with the remote repository and you are ready to integrate those latest changes right away.
